Computation of the apparent mean velocity of ground-water flow follows directly from the mean traveltime: d (eq. 12) G==-, 3600 i where ; d 3600 Y = = = = mean-flow velocity, in feet per second (ft/s); map distance of the trace, in feet; a unit conversion factor, and mean traveltime, in hours.
Because the exact flow path and distance between the dye input and recovery points is not known, d and ~ are apparent values, computed as if the dye followed a straight line between the points.
Thus, the actual flow velocity is probably somewhat greater than the apparent velocity because of the longer, meandering nature of the actual flow path in most karst aquifers.
The term~ does give, however, a general idea of ground-water velocity that may be compared between dye traces for different flow conditions.
It may also be used in estimating the dispersion coefficient discussed in section 4.2.4.
The standard deviation of the time of travel of the dye mass is a temporal measure of the amount of dispersion of the dye mass that occurred during the dye trace.
In other words, it indicates how much the dye cloud has spread out in time, between the injection and the sampling site.
It is related to the time of travel and the rate of dispersion, and is computed by the equation: 9 0.5 ; (ti-;)' Ci
