The standard deviation of traveltime is used in creating the dimensionless dye-recovery curve, in calculating the dispersion coefficient, and in developing relations among the quantitative characteristics and discharge.
Because it is a measure of the total amount of dispersion that has taken place, Ot generally increases when the time of travel is long or when the rate of dispersion is great.
The skewness coefficient is a measure of the lateral asymmetry of the time-concentration curve.
